# {{PROJECT_NAME}} — CI checks standard (the inherited brain-checks gate)

Every brain runs an inherited **`brain-checks`** CI workflow — the self-extending
brain's anti-drift, intent, and docs-mesh gate. It runs on every `pull_request`
and on every `push` to `main`, and it is the mechanism that keeps a brain's map,
commands, and docs honest as the brain grows.

The workflow ships in the hub at
`brain-template/.github/workflows/brain-checks.yml`; every provisioned brain
inherits it and keeps it in sync.

## The gates

`brain-checks` runs three checks. Two are **always blocking**; the third is
blocking by default with a narrow, documented escape hatch.

### Blocking — `capabilities --check` (anti-drift)

`python -m brainfactory capabilities --brain <dir> --check` regenerates the
capability model from code (the command directories + the manifest) and fails if
the committed `01-docs/CAPABILITIES.md` does not match what the generator
derives. The map may not drift from the code: if you change what the brain can
do, the committed map must change with it. There is **no** allowance to make this
check non-blocking.

### Blocking — `intent-gate` (no command without a capabilities row)

`python -m brainfactory intent-gate --brain <dir>` fails if any command directory
under `core/` or `extensions/` has no row in the committed `CAPABILITIES.md`. A
feature cannot land without the brain growing with it — every command the brain
gains must be reflected in its map. There is **no** allowance to make this check
non-blocking.

### Blocking by default — `docs-mesh` (links, wikilinks, mermaid, freshness)

`python -m brainfactory docs-mesh --brain <dir>` fails if links, wikilinks, or
mermaid blocks do not resolve and balance, or if a freshness stamp does not
parse. It is **blocking by default**.

#### The escape hatch (narrow, honest, temporary)

A lane MAY mark **one** check `continue-on-error: true` **only** for a
**pre-existing, unresolvable** finding it genuinely cannot fix within the scope
of the current change. When it does, it MUST:

- leave a `TODO(<lane>-docs-mesh)` at the exact site (or in the workflow step)
  naming what is unresolved and why it is out of scope; and
- emit a `::warning::` from the step so the soft-failed gate is loud in the CI
  log, never silent.

It MUST **never fake-pass**: do not repoint a link to something it does not mean,
and do not edit an append-only log (continuity `05-logs/`, the decision board) to
make the mesh resolve. Those defeat the gate instead of satisfying it. The escape
hatch buys time to fix a real, scoped-out problem; it does not license hiding one.

> **Precedent.** Contoso carries a `TODO(contoso-docs-mesh)` for exactly this case — a
> pre-existing unresolvable it soft-failed with a `::warning::` and a tracked
> TODO, rather than faking a green mesh. That is the reference shape for the
> escape hatch: visible, attributed, and time-boxed.

## Inheritance

The gate is **inherited, not reinvented**. It ships in
`brain-template/.github/workflows/brain-checks.yml`; every provisioned brain gets
it and keeps it in sync with the hub. A lane MAY adjust the wiring it must
(e.g. `BRAINFACTORY_PYTHONPATH` / `BRAIN_DIR` for where its adapters and brain
root live), but it **documents any local deviation** rather than silently forking
the gate. The three invariants above are the contract; the wiring is negotiable,
the invariants are not.

## The superset allowance

A lane MAY ship a **richer, bespoke capabilities generator** in place of the
standard `python -m brainfactory` generator — **provided its CI still enforces
the same three invariants** (PR-time capabilities drift-check, intent parity, and
docs-mesh). A generator that covers *more* than brain commands is a valid
**superset**, not a violation.

Concretely, a lane whose product is more than a brain (an app API, broker
adapters, config keys, scheduled workflows) MAY generate a **system-wide
capability map** — one that inventories app API routes, adapters, config keys, and
workflows, not just the brain's command directories — and drift-check *that*
richer map on every PR. As long as the brain-command invariants remain enforced
(the map still fails on drift, every command still needs a row, the mesh still
resolves), the superset **satisfies** this standard.

> **Reference superset.** Northwind (`izakl/northwind-autonomy-system`) ships
> `08-ops/generate-capabilities.ps1`, a system-wide generator that maps the whole
> autonomy system — app API routes, broker adapters, config keys, and workflows —
> not only brain commands. Its CI drift-checks that superset map and keeps the
> intent + docs-mesh invariants, so it complies **via the superset allowance**
> rather than by running the stock generator. This is a superset, not a fork:
> the standard's three invariants are still enforced, over a broader surface.

